<TITLE> Cabinet okays telecoms, real estate laws </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 20 (bdnews24.com)  The interim cabinet has provisionally approved the Bangladesh Telecommunications Amendment Ordinance-2008, a spokesman said. It has also declared the offences listed in the Real Estate Development and Management Ordinance, 2008 non-bailable. The cabinet at a meeting on Thursday however asked officials to table the amended telecoms ordinance before it after scrutiny by the law ministry, the chief adviser's press secretary Syed Fahim Munaim said after the meeting. "The revised ordinance proposes that the Bangladesh Telecommunications Regulatory Commission will act in line with the guidelines of the ordinance. The commissioner's tenure shall be four years instead of three years. It will prepare and place report to the ministry 120 days after every fiscal year" BTRC will draft the budget that the finance ministry will approve, he pointed out. Thursday's cabinet meeting approved proposal to seek time extension of a court stay order on unified education in ninth and tenth grade, the re-introduction of Government Attorney Services Ordinance-2008 and the finalisation of the Real Estate Development and Management Ordinance-2008. Munaim said joint initiatives from public and private sectors had been allowed in the real estate ordinance that aims to protect the interests of both buyers and sellers. "The meeting has approved punitive measures including two-year jail term or a fine of up to Tk 10 lakh or both for the real estate firms that carry out works or advertise without prior approval from the appropriate authorities. The provisions of one year in jail or Tk 5 lakh fine or both for cancelling or suspending allotment without notifying the clients or for stopping real estate works are also there. Realtors face three-year jail term or a fine of up to Tk 20 lakh or both for construction beyond the approved design and two years in jail or a fine of Tk 20 lakh or both for deception, the press secretary said. bdnews24.
